description: The genus Pseudacris correlates to chorus frogs; Hyla to treefrogs.  If one accepts Pseudacris, then the correct epithet is chorus frog, Central Pacific Chorus Frog.

This was on the return from the palm oasis - on the higher trail above the canyon.

We also saw a Coachwhip, but he slipped quickly into a hole in a rock!

description: This is an interesting shell I found years ago in Healdsburg, California. It is a VERY small H. arrosa type with a mature well developed peristome. It is well malleated and wrinkled along the surface but also exhibits striated lines of growth...weird. The shell is very depressed in shape with a fully open umbilicus. I sent the specimen to Barry Roth for examination.
Found near the lake edge. Shell around 20-25 mm wide.
